@vinothchandar 
Sorry for delay. I've changed my job in February, and my new job works for an automobile company. This company use HDP 3.1 with hadoop3 and spark2.3 and hive3.1. Because the version of hadoop and hive is too high, the new job is not using hudi for the time being.
Recently, my team is going to launch a new data lake project. My work is busy, so I don't have much time to pay attention to it in May. I'll do it in April and add some new research after that.

@leilinen did you have the same problem with this patch applied as well? 

Some background. FileSystem class caches and hands out references of FileSystem object across a jvm (i.e driver or . single executor) and also registers hooks to close the cached instances when shutting down.. So that will take care of reclaiming resources.. 

@n3nash Not following.  General practice for spark apps is to not call fs.close() at all and Hudi should be no different.. However as @bvaradar pointed out to me, may be its worth calling `super.close()` just in case.. I ll send in a PR for that.. If you still see follow up to be done, please open a JIRA and we can discuss and prioritize there

@arunlakshman Thanks for starting a contribution to the project! I'm not fully following the intent of this PR. The issue HUDI-61 may not be valid anymore since we do not have the payload class dependency in the SpillableMap anymore. 

Right now, any implementation of HoodieRecordPayload can use the SpillableMap and this is not limited to HoodieAvroPayload. 

Do you have any custom implementation of HoodieRecordPayload that you intend to use ? Are you running into any specific issue ? Happy to help out once I know the underlying issue you are facing.

@renwei111 : 
The other way to skip integration test is to run 

mvn clean install **-DskipITs** -DskipTests -Dhadoop.version=2.6.0-cdh5.7.2 -Dhive.version=1.1.0-cdh5.7.2
